SIMPLE: indigested
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Indigested
<hw>In`di*gest"ed</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>in-</ets> not +
<ets>digested</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Not digested; undigested.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Indigested</xex> food.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not resolved; not regularly disposed and arranged;
not methodical; crude; <as>as, an <ex>indigested</ex> array of
facts</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In hot reformations . . . the whole is generally crude, harsh, and
<qex>indigested</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This, like an <qex>indigested</qex> meteor, appeared and
disappeared almost at the same time.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Not in a state
suitable for healing; -- said of wounds.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Not
ripened or suppurated; -- said of an abscess or its contents.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Not softened by heat, hot water, or steam.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indigestedness</ent>⟦br⟧
